Rating: 3
This was FAB - but I had to contend with what I had on hand. There was some beef of dubious origin (hubby bought meat REALLY on sale and there was lots of "stuff" to trim) so I thought that a long simmer might be the best way to go. I put the broth and mustard in my crock-pot and cranked it up to high. I ended up adding more mustard so I probably had about 1/3 cup in there. Needed some tartness. The meat got seared with olive oil over pretty high heat, then set to the side to rest in a bowl (not sure why they specify a baking sheet??? Let the pan cool off for a couple of minutes to medium and then added about 1 Tbs olive oil to gently saute an onion and garlic mix (no shallots). After a couple of minutes (soft, but not browning) I tossed in mushrooms that I had cut into quarters (anticipating the long crock-pot time). Cooked this at medium to med-hi for a couple of minutes to get the mushrooms glossy. Added at least 1/4 cup of sherry (no cognac in the house) and tossed that around for only a minute or so until it was frisky. Put the meat back in to get the juices all chummy with each other and warm the meat back up. I waited for the liquid to cook down just a bit, then tossed it all into the crock-pot and left it on hi for 2-3 hours. Taste intermittently to make sure seasoning is ok. Right before serving, I added my sour cream (no creme fraiche - remember this is peasant food) and blended it gently over medium heat before serving over Kasha. WOW!!!

Rating: 4
A HIT!! We will definately have this one agian. Even our 19 month old daughter devoured it. I did make some changes only because I was working with what was in my house. They are as followed: No butter, I used only a total of 6 Tbls of Olive Oil, I added 1 Tbls of minced Garlic to the onions, I used baby bellas (great flavor) I did not have Cognac so I used 2Tbls of semi-sweet red wine and 1Tbls Whiskey, 1/2 cup of sour cream instead of creme fraiche and spicey brown mustard instead of dijon. I used Wacky Mac, because we did not have egg noodles and added parsley to the noodles with the olive oil. YUMMY and PERFECT!!

Rating: 1
After reading all the rave reviews, I decided to make this and it was a let down. My mom always made a delicious stroganoff and this just couldn't hold a candle - it was soupy, the meat did not have time to tenderize bc of the short cook time, and all in all, the flavor was not that great. I am usually fairly adventurous with spices, but I thought the dill contributed nothing and left an odd aftertaste. If I make it again, I will use 1/4 whipping cream, 1/2 cup sour cream, no dill, more onion/shallot, more cognac, reserve the mushrooms until the last 15 minutes so they dont get too mushy, and cook on low for enough time to make the beef tender and melt-in-your-mouth. Also, my mom always used a dash of nutmeg and it gives a good flavor - much more so than the dill.

