Rating: 4
This is a fabulous recipe -- rich and succulent. I was able to find precut beef tenderloin labeled as "stroganoff strips" (presumably cut from tenderloin end pieces too small to sell as whole roasts) for much less than a tenderloin roast would have been, and I'm very glad I did. The tenderness of the beef is a huge part of this dish's appeal. I made a few changes based on what I already had in the pantry -- onions (cut into half-rings) for the shallots, sour cream for the creme fraiche, and dry sherry for the Cognac. The flavors of the dill and the mustard make this recipe stand out as something special. It's important to let the beef broth and sherry/Cognac cook down to almost nothing before adding the pan juices and sour cream, or the final sauce will be watery. When the sour cream forms the body of the sauce, it develops a wonderfully silky texture that clings to the beef, mushrooms, and noodles.

