Rating: 3
This can be delicious even when using a cut of beef intended for braising, i.e.round, chuck or shoulder. (Husband brought home a mystery cut). Dredge in flour, braise (brown) in dutch oven, in 1 tab. olive oil & 1 tab. butter, both sides on high heat, e careful not to burn. Season with seasoned salt, garlic powder, onion powder & fresh ground black pepper. Remove beef to cutting board, cut in 1" x 3/8" pieces. Return to pan. Add 1 can (14.5 oz.) beef broth, 1/4 cup red wine, 1 tab. tomato sauce, cover & simmer 1 hour. In a separate pan, saute 1 small chopped onion. Add to beef. After 1 hour, to 3 Tab. flour, add pan juices and stir to form paste. Add back to pan, stir until thick, cook about 5 min. on moderate heat. Turn off heat and set aside. Saute in separate pan, 8 oz. sliced mushrooms in 2 tab. butter (mod. high heat) until brown, add 1 tab. cognac. Before serving, stir in 3/4 cup sour cream, add mushrooms. Serve over narrow curly noodles. Sprinkle with Paprika

Rating: 4
Superb! I followed the recipe exactly so that I could give it a fair review. The tenderloin though seemingly extravagant to be layered in sauce was definitely a must. It's tenderness allows the flavors to roll through each taste bud in your mouth, without the distraction of a heavy chew. The creme' fraiche too is a necessary indulgence, it gives the dish a unique but subtle tartness not often found in american dishes. For the non-experimental types, the addition of dill may seem scary, but go for it. Please don't leave out the cognac. It imparts a richness to the dish without a trace of an alcohol flavor. Follow the timing as stated and this will be an excellent dish for you and your guests. Enjoy!

