Rating: 2
"Stroganoff," in whatever spelling, like "gulyash," has come to be a generic word describing almost any dish (or cafeteria slop) with beef and cream, and which, like this recipe, bears little resemblance to the original. A couple of corrections. The dish has not been around for "hundreds of years." It is a 19th cent. dish concoted by a French chef for one Pierre Stroganov. The earliest identifiable references to the dish contain either sour cream (Russian preference) or creme fraische (French twist). No mention of cognac, though it does add a touch as does the dill. PLEASE,PLEASE: Straw potatoes only, not "noodles," yuck!

